data.name: PRT_PWV_TEXT_3
data.value:
Pulse Wave Velocity is the internationally recognised measure for determining the stiffness of your arteries. Because your aorta is directly connected to all the important organs (brain, heart, kidneys), the stiffness of this artery from your neck to the top of the leg, has been shown to be the best predictor of your cardiovascular risk.
Your doctor has placed a probe, called tonometer, on your carotid artery (neck) and a cuff around your femoral artery (leg). The cuff and the tonometer have measured how long your heart beat (or pulse) took to travel from your neck to your leg.
If your arteries are young and/or healthy, the arteries are supple and relaxed, and the pulse travels slowly along the aorta. As we get older, our arteries get stiffer and make the pulse travel faster. Smoking, lack of exercise, hypertension and diabetes can all prematurely stiffen your arteries.
Using these time measurements and the length of your arteries, the speed of your pulse (called Pulse Wave Velocity) can be calculated:

data.name: PRT_PWA_TEXT_RPT_DESCRIPTION
data.value: The Global Standard in Pulse Wave Analysis

data.name: RPT_PWATEXT1
data.value: This report explains your Pulse Wave Analysis measurement, a test used to assess your Central Blood pressure (the pressure at your heart) and the stiffness of your arterial system.

data.name: RPT_PWATEXT2
data.value: How is Pulse Wave Analysis different to normal cuff Blood pressure measurements?

data.name: RPT_PWATEXT3
data.value:
When your Blood pressure is measured at your arm, your Doctor is measuring:
a) the highest pressure reached in your arm (the systolic pressure).
b) the lowest pressure measured in your arm ( the diastolic pressure).
If your Doctor tells you your Blood pressure is 120 over 80 (often written like 120/80) then your systolic pressure is 120 and your diastolic pressure is 80.
The SphygmoCor Pulse Wave Analysis device provides this information, and 2 other important measurements:
a) Central Blood pressure – this is the pressure in the aorta, the large artery carrying blood from the heart to the body. Many studies have shown that your central blood pressure is a better indicator of your risk of heart attack, stroke, diabetes and kidney disease than normal cuff pressure.
b) Arterial stiffness – this is a measure of the elasticity of your arteries. The less elastic your arteries (or the stiffer your arteries are), the more likely you are to have hypertension or high blood pressure.

data.name: RPT_PWATEXT4
data.value: What is arterial stiffness and how is this related to my Blood pressure?

data.name: RPT_PWATEXT5
data.value: High central blood pressure is often caused by stiffening or hardening of the arteries. Your heart pumps blood through your arteries via the aorta, the major artery in your body. The blood moves around the arterial system in waves.

data.name: RPT_PWATEXT6
data.value:
Wherever the arteries break into smaller arteries, some of the pressure from the wave can be reflected back towards the heart. In young patients, the arteries will stretch and pressure reflected back to the heart is small or non existent.
However, as we get older, and our arteries get stiffer, the pressure reflected back to the heart becomes greater. Over time, this increased pressure creates more work for the heart as it must pump the blood against this “back pressure” caused by the stiffness of the arterial system. This is why it is important to measure the pressure at your heart as well as at your arm, and your arterial stiffness.

Your central Pulse pressure is your central systolic pressure minus your central diastolic pressure. It represents the change in pressure in your arteries every heart beat.
Studies in the USA have shown that a central Pulse pressure of more than 50mmHG increases your risk of heart attack and stroke.

The green line on the graph below shows the healthy level of central Pulse pressure from the age of 20 to the age of 90 years old. The red lines show an acceptable range of Pulse pressure for each age.

data.name: RPT_PWATEXT26
data.value:
If your measurement is on or below the green line: Congratulations, your central Pulse pressure is normal for your age or lower than normal for your age.
If your measurement is between the green line and the top red line, then your central Pulse pressure is normal but is at the higher end of the normal range. You should continue to monitor your central Pulse pressure regularly with visits to your Doctor to make sure it is not increasing.
If your measurement is above the top red line, or above 50mmHG, your central Pulse pressure is high compared to others your age. Talk to your doctor about things you can do to reduce your central Pulse pressure, such as:

data.name: RPT_PWATEXT36
data.value:
Your central Augmented pressure is the additional pressure measured at your heart due to the stiffness of your arteries. When your arteries are not stiff, the Augmented pressure will be low.
Studies have shown that high central Augmented pressure is related to kidney failure and dementia, as increased arterial stiffness increases the pressure in the small arteries in the kidney and the brain.
Your central Augmented pressure is {0}.
The green line on the graph below shows the healthy level of Augemented pressure from the age of 20 to the age of 90 years old. The red lines show an acceptable range of Augmented pressure for each age.

data.name: RPT_PWATEXT37
data.value:
If your measurement is on or below the green line: Congratulations, your central Augmented pressure, and therefore your arterial stiffness, are normal for your age or lower than normal for your age.
If your measurement is between the green line and the top red line, then your central Augmented pressure and arterial stiffness are normal but at the higher end of the normal range. You should continue to monitor your arterial stiffness regularly with your Doctor to make sure it is not increasing.
If your measurement is above the top red line, your central Augmented pressure and arterial stiffness are high compared to others your age. Talk to your Doctor about lifestyle changes and/or medication that can reduce your arterial stiffness.

data.name: RPT_PWATEXT39

Your central Augmentation index is another measure of your arterial stiffness. When your arteries are not stiff, the central Augmentation index will be lower.
Central Augmentation index can provide an early indication of arterial stiffness, well before the arterial stiffness results in an increase in cuff pressure.

data.name: RPT_PWATEXT40
data.value:
If your measurement is on or below the green line: Congratulations, your central Augmentation index, and therefore your arterial stiffness are normal for your age or lower than normal for your age.
If your measurement is between the green line and the top red line, then your central Augmentation index and arterial stiffness are normal but at the higher end of the normal range. You should continue to monitor your Central Augmentation index when you visit your Doctor to make sure your arterial stiffness is not increasing.
If your measurement is above the top red line, your central Augmentation index and arterial stiffness are high compared to others your age. Your Doctor will discuss appropriate lifestyle modifications and /or medication with you.
